    "message_1": "Suppose you are given the following set of data: (1.2, 2.1), (2.5, 4.7), (4.1, 2.8), and (5.8, 6.5). Use Lagrange interpolation to estimate the value of y at x = 3.7.",
    "message_2": "To estimate the value of y at x = 3.7 using Lagrange interpolation, we will use the formula:\n\ny(x) = L(x) = L_0(x) * y_0 + L_1(x) * y_1 + L_2(x) * y_2 + L_3(x) * y_3\n\nwhere L_i(x) are the Lagrange basis polynomials and y_i are the y-values of the given data points.\n\nGiven data points: (1.2, 2.1), (2.5, 4.7), (4.1, 2.8), and (5.8, 6.5)\n\nL_0(x) = ((x - x_1)(x - x_2)(x - x_3)) / ((x_0 - x_1)(x_0 - x_2)(x_0 - x_3))\nL_1(x) = ((x - x_0)(x - x_2)(x - x_3)) / ((x_1 - x_0)(x_1 - x_2)(x_1 - x_3))\nL_2(x) = ((x - x_0)(x - x_1)(x - x_3)) / ((x_2 - x_0)(x_2 - x_1)(x_2 - x_3))\nL_3(x) = ((x - x_0)(x - x_1)(x - x_2)) / ((x_3 - x_0)(x_3 - x_1)(x_3 - x_2))\n\nNow, we will calculate the Lagrange basis polynomials for x = 3.7:\n\nL_0(3.7) = ((3.7 - 2.5)(3.7 - 4.1)(3.7 - 5.8)) / ((1.2 - 2.5)(1.2 - 4.1)(1.2 - 5.8)) ≈ 0.0986\nL_1(3.7) = ((3.7 - 1.2)(3.7 - 4.1)(3.7 - 5.8)) / ((2.5 - 1.2)(2.5 - 4.1)(2.5 - 5.8)) ≈ 0.4810\nL_2(3.7) = ((3.7 - 1.2)(3.7 - 2.5)(3.7 - 5.8)) / ((4.1 - 1.2)(4.1 - 2.5)(4.1 - 5.8)) ≈ 0.4642\nL_3(3.7) = ((3.7 - 1.2)(3.7 - 2.5)(3.7 - 4.1)) / ((5.8 - 1.2)(5.8 - 2.5)(5.8 - 4.1)) ≈ -0.0438\n\nNow, we will use the Lagrange interpolation formula:\n\ny(3.7) = L_0(3.7) * y_0 + L_1(3.7) * y_1 + L_2(3.7) * y_2 + L_3(3.7) * y_3\ny(3.7) = 0.0986 * 2.1 + 0.4810 * 4.7 + 0.4642 * 2.8 + (-0.0438) * 6.5 ≈ 3.9194\n\nSo, the estimated value of y at x = 3.7 using Lagrange interpolation is approximately 3.9194."
